  "title": "Authority and Family",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ebc4b33c84596415",
      "text": "The relationship between authority and the family under investigation is not thought of as static. According to the authors of the study [Studien über Autorität und Familie [Studies on authority and the family] [https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1937-04654-001 page]], as society changes, so do the functions and relationships of people within the family, which in turn affects the development of the human psyche and the capacity for \"specifically authoritarian behavior\" mentioned by Horkheimer. The \"changes in the psychic structure\" are therefore also considered \"as moments of a process whose rhythm in the history so far has been dictated by the unfolding and erratic transformation of the relationship of man to the given nature in the reproduction of his life, that is, by economic necessity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4781707983907592",
      "text": "[…] The starting point of Fromm's reflections is the peculiar interlocking of coercion and voluntariness that can be observed in certain character types in their relationship to authority or submission to it, and thus also the \"satisfaction that the relationship to authority obviously has for many of those subjected to it, that pleasure in obedience and submission\". Fromm states in his essay that \"the love of the stronger grows on an extremely ambivalent emotional basis.\" This ambivalence is often expressed in such a way that the powerful are [[divide]]d into two groups: to some all good qualities are attributed and they are loved, to others all bad qualities and they are hated. Fromm's remarks were later to form an important aspect in the analysis of anti-Semitism, as carried out, for example, by Adorno in his studies on the authoritarian character and, together with Horkheimer, in the Dialectic of Enlightenment."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "56f33329b63edd8e",
      "text": "He also takes up once again in general terms the lack of potential for effective revolt against oppressive power, as Fromm had already empirically analyzed it in view of the absence of a large-scale uprising of the German proletariat against National Socialism in the study of workers and employees: The lack of ability to effectively combat oppressive violence \"or, to put it another way, the lack of offensive potency is the negative characteristic of this character's relationship to authority. This lack extends as much to action as to thought. He may well be driven in some circumstances to defiant revolt against the existing power, but he will usually then commit himself to a new one.\" This attitude is an expression of the ambivalence mentioned above, which does not weaken \"the more cause there is in reality for hatred of a particular authority\" but, on the contrary, strengthens and can even be functionalized by the hated authority by encouraging and supporting the division mentioned above \"because in this way the double aim can be achieved of keeping the relationship with it itself free from hatred and, on the other hand, of directing hatred against such powers as it wishes to combat with the help of those subordinate to it.\" The renunciation of \"imposing one's own will against that of the stronger\" still leaves the pleasure of savoring \"the feeling of power through the unrestrained domination of the weaker\": \"and what means more domination than to make him suffer!\""
